      <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA10d138n4-ptr" id="PJA10d138n4">4</a>
       
   <p>In fact, the tea that was stored underneath the Exchange at Charleston was ulti-<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-10-02-pb-0203">[203<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-10/ADMS-06-10-02-pb-0203.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>mately sold to finance the war effort (Robert M. Weir, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Colonial South Carolina</span>, Millwood, N.Y., 1983, p. 313).</p>

      </div>
      <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA10d138n5-ptr" id="PJA10d138n5">5</a>
       
